From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Wed, 24 Jun 2026 08:19:13 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] kati: move global variable bindings off the symtab onto the
 Evaluator
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Make variables used to live in the process-global symbol table
(Symtab::symbol_data), so every kati invocation in a process shared one
variable namespace. That is wrong for in-process sub-makes (a sub-make must
start with a fresh namespace, inheriting only exported env) and unsafe once
multiple kati instances run in one process — the prerequisite for running
embedded make as a proper in-process brush builtin.

Split the symbol table: the interner (name<->id) stays global (Symbol ids
must be stable), but the variable *bindings* move to a per-instance store on
the Evaluator (`global_vars: Arc<Mutex<Vec<Option<Var>>>>`). The accessors
(get/peek/set/clear_global_var, get_symbol_names) and the variable-precedence
logic (readonly / override / command-line-beats-file / automatic-overwrite)
move verbatim onto the Evaluator; the special vars (.SHELLSTATUS / .VARIABLES
/ .KATI_SYMBOLS) and the automatic vars ($@/$</$^/...) are now seeded per
instance instead of once into the global symtab. ScopedGlobalVar holds an
Arc<Mutex> handle to the store so its Drop restore still works without an
&Evaluator (so $@/$(D)/$(F) under .SECONDEXPANSION and foreach/call temp vars
survive ?-early-returns). Added Symbol::index()/from_index() so the store can
be indexed by symbol id.

All call sites (eval/var/command/dep/func/main + the engine's katirun glue)
now route through `ev`. Behavior is unchanged for a single instance: the
standalone corpus holds at KATI_COMPAT_PASS=364/378, fail=0. A bonus of
killing the global is that the Evaluator's variable handling is now
unit-testable in isolation.

This is step 1 of converting embedded make/ninja into proper in-process
brush builtins on logical shell state; the FUSE-shadow/main() entrypoint is
left intact.

